hook.real_world_problem:
Look at the Inventory refactor from last topic:

```java
catalog[0] = new Product();
catalog[0].id = 101;
catalog[0].name = "Wireless Mouse";
catalog[0].stock = 45;
catalog[0].price = 599.99;
```

Five lines just to create one product. Multiply by 100 products and you have 500 lines of repetitive setup code. Worse: if you forget to set a field, you have a Product with `price = 0` or `name = null` — a quietly broken object that explodes later.

**Constructors solve this.** A constructor lets you create an object AND set its fields in ONE line:

```java
catalog[0] = new Product(101, "Wireless Mouse", 45, 599.99);
```

One line. All fields initialized. Java even FORCES you to provide values if you design the constructor that way — no more half-initialized objects.

But constructors do more than save typing. They're the GATEKEEPER of object validity. A constructor can validate input and refuse to create nonsense objects: 'No, you cannot create a Product with negative stock.' This is how professional Java code prevents bugs at the source.

This topic is when your OOP code stops looking amateurish and starts looking professional.

concept_explanation.the_default_constructor:
If you don't write any constructor, Java provides a **default no-arg constructor** automatically. That's what you've been using:

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;
    // No constructor written — Java provides:
    // public Dog() { }
}

// You can do:
Dog d = new Dog();  // Calls the implicit no-arg constructor
```

The default constructor:
- Takes no parameters
- Has empty body
- Sets all fields to their default values (0, false, null)

This is why `new Dog()` works without you writing a constructor. **But the moment you write ANY constructor, Java stops providing the default.** You have to write a no-arg constructor explicitly if you want one.

concept_explanation.writing_a_constructor:
**Basic constructor with parameters**:

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;

    public Dog(String dogName, int dogAge) {
        name = dogName;
        age = dogAge;
    }
}
```

Now you can create dogs in one line:

```java
Dog rex = new Dog("Rex", 3);
Dog buddy = new Dog("Buddy", 5);

System.out.println(rex.name);   // Rex
System.out.println(buddy.age);  // 5
```

**What happens**: `new Dog("Rex", 3)` allocates memory, calls `Dog("Rex", 3)` constructor, which assigns name="Rex" and age=3, then returns the configured Dog.

Notice:
- `public Dog(...)` — constructor signature
- NO return type before `Dog` — not even `void`
- Parameter names `dogName`, `dogAge` are DIFFERENT from field names
- Body assigns parameter values to fields

The convention of different parameter names is awkward. There's a better way using `this`.

concept_explanation.the_this_keyword:
**`this`** is a special reference that means 'the current object' — the one whose method is running right now.

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;

    public Dog(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;   // this.name (field) = name (parameter)
        this.age = age;
    }
}
```

Now parameter names MATCH field names. `this.name` is the field, `name` (alone) is the parameter. Without `this.`, Java assumes you mean the parameter (closest scope).

**Why this is better**: the parameter name conveys MEANING ("this is the name parameter"). The `this.` is just disambiguation when needed. Reading code becomes natural.

**When you need `this.`**:
- Constructor with parameters same name as fields (most common)
- Method that returns the object itself (`return this;`)
- Passing the current object to another method (`other.compare(this)`)

**When you don't need `this.`**:
- Accessing fields when no name conflict exists
- Calling instance methods of the same object (`bark()` not `this.bark()`)

Both work — `this.bark()` is legal but verbose. Most Java code skips it when no conflict exists.

concept_explanation.constructor_overloading:
Java allows MULTIPLE constructors with different parameter lists (this is **overloading**, same concept from Module 2 methods).

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;
    String breed;

    // Constructor 1: full info
    public Dog(String name, int age, String breed) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    // Constructor 2: just name and age
    public Dog(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.breed = "Unknown";
    }

    // Constructor 3: just name
    public Dog(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = 0;
        this.breed = "Unknown";
    }

    // Constructor 4: no-arg
    public Dog() {
        this.name = "Unnamed";
        this.age = 0;
        this.breed = "Unknown";
    }
}
```

All four work:

```java
Dog d1 = new Dog("Rex", 3, "Labrador");
Dog d2 = new Dog("Buddy", 5);
Dog d3 = new Dog("Luna");
Dog d4 = new Dog();
```

Java picks the matching constructor based on the arguments you provide.

**Overloading rules** (same as methods):
- Different NUMBER of parameters, OR
- Different TYPES of parameters
- Same name, different signature

**Why overload constructors?** Flexibility. Sometimes you have all the info, sometimes just some. The caller picks the constructor that matches their data.

concept_explanation.constructor_chaining:
Repeating field assignments across 4 constructors is ugly. Java lets one constructor CALL another using `this(...)`.

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;
    String breed;

    public Dog(String name, int age, String breed) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    public Dog(String name, int age) {
        this(name, age, "Unknown");   // calls the 3-arg constructor
    }

    public Dog(String name) {
        this(name, 0, "Unknown");     // calls the 3-arg constructor
    }

    public Dog() {
        this("Unnamed", 0, "Unknown");
    }
}
```

Much cleaner. All four constructors funnel to the main one, which is the ONLY place fields are assigned.

**Rules for `this(...)`**:
- Must be the FIRST line of the constructor
- Can only appear in constructors (not regular methods)
- The called constructor runs first; then the calling constructor's body continues

This pattern — called **constructor chaining** — is everywhere in production Java. Real codebases have one 'primary' constructor that does all the work, with convenience constructors that delegate to it.

concept_explanation.validation_in_constructors:
The most powerful thing constructors do: REJECT invalid input.

```java
public class Product {
    int id;
    String name;
    int stock;
    double price;

    public Product(int id, String name, int stock, double price) {
        if (id <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("ID must be positive");
        }
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name cannot be empty");
        }
        if (stock < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Stock cannot be negative");
        }
        if (price < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Price cannot be negative");
        }

        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.stock = stock;
        this.price = price;
    }
}
```

**Now you cannot create a broken Product**:

```java
Product good = new Product(101, "Mouse", 45, 599.99);  // works
Product bad = new Product(-1, "Mouse", 45, 599.99);    // throws exception!
Product bad2 = new Product(101, "", 45, 599.99);       // throws exception!
Product bad3 = new Product(101, "Mouse", -5, 599.99);  // throws exception!
```

**This is HUGE.** Compare to the previous version where anyone could do `product.stock = -100` after creation. Now:
1. Invalid data is rejected at the source (during creation)
2. Once an object exists, it's GUARANTEED valid (assuming constructor validation passes)
3. Errors happen where they originate, not later when buggy data crashes something

**`IllegalArgumentException`**: a built-in exception for 'caller passed bad data.' We'll cover exceptions in detail later, but for now: throwing one stops the constructor and propagates an error to the caller.

**Production note**: This is defensive programming. The constructor is your last line of defense before bad data gets into the system. Spend effort here — it pays dividends.

concept_explanation.constructor_vs_method:
Quick comparison to clarify the distinction:

| Aspect | Constructor | Regular Method |
|--------|-------------|----------------|
| Name | Same as class | Anything (verb) |
| Return type | None (not even void) | Required (void or type) |
| When called | Automatically by `new` | Manually by code |
| Purpose | Initialize new object | Perform operations |
| Can be called multiple times | No (once per object) | Yes |
| Can be static? | No | Yes |
| Can be overloaded? | Yes | Yes |

**Common confusion**: Java doesn't prevent you from writing a METHOD with the same name as the class. But it WILL be just a method, not a constructor, because:

```java
public class Dog {
    public void Dog() {       // This is a METHOD (has void return type)
        System.out.println("Method");
    }

    public Dog() {             // This is a CONSTRUCTOR (no return type)
        System.out.println("Constructor");
    }
}
```

The difference: presence or absence of return type. If there's any return type (including void), it's a method.

This trips up beginners constantly: a 'constructor' with `void` is just a method that never gets called by `new`.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
class Product {
    int id;
    String name;
    int stock;
    double price;

    public Product(int id, String name, int stock, double price) {
        if (id <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("ID must be positive, got: " + id);
        }
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name cannot be empty");
        }
        if (stock < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Stock cannot be negative, got: " + stock);
        }
        if (price < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Price cannot be negative, got: " + price);
        }

        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.stock = stock;
        this.price = price;
    }
}
```

Four validation checks. Each error message includes what was wrong (the actual value) — crucial for debugging.

```java
public String describe() {
    return "#" + id + " " + name + " — Stock: " + stock + ", Price: ₹" + price;
}
```

The method works the same as before. Constructors changed how the object is BUILT, but methods that use the object don't care.

```java
public class InventoryV2 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // ONE LINE per product now!
        Product[] catalog = new Product[5];
        catalog[0] = new Product(101, "Wireless Mouse", 45, 599.99);
        catalog[1] = new Product(102, "USB-C Cable", 12, 249.0);
        catalog[2] = new Product(103, "Notebook", 87, 89.5);
        catalog[3] = new Product(104, "Mechanical Keyboard", 8, 4500.0);
        catalog[4] = new Product(105, "Desk Lamp", 23, 1299.0);

        System.out.println("=== INVENTORY (V2 with Constructors) ===");
        for (Product p : catalog) {
            System.out.println(p.describe());
        }
    }
}
```

**Compare to Topic 4.1**: 25 lines of setup → 5 lines. Each Product is initialized fully in one call.

Add at end of main:

```java
// Try to create an invalid product
try {
    Product bad = new Product(-1, "Broken", 10, 99.99);
    System.out.println("This should not print");
} catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
    System.out.println("\nRejected bad product: " + e.getMessage());
}

// Negative price
try {
    Product bad2 = new Product(999, "Weird", 0, -50.0);
} catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
    System.out.println("Rejected bad product: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

The `try/catch` catches the exception so the program continues. We'll cover exceptions formally in a later module — for now, the syntax is:
- `try { ... }` — code that might throw
- `catch (ExceptionType e) { ... }` — runs if that exception type is thrown
- `e.getMessage()` — the error message from the exception

**Result**: Bad products are REJECTED. They never become objects. The error is reported. Program continues.

```java
// Using the 3-arg constructor (stock defaults to 0)
Product partial = new Product(106, "Out of Stock Item", 199.0);
System.out.println("\nPartial product: " + partial.describe());
```

This Product has stock=0 (set by the chained constructor). Useful when stock is unknown at creation time.

